segments.text: As you can imagine, the cost of building a nuclear power plant and a coal-fired plant is extremely high on the front end.
So the city is having to float bonds to pay for this high cost at the front end.
I think with the knowledge that as you move on out into the future, those costs are going to be very, very low.
And what we're talking about in the future is fuel costs.
So the utility rates are high.
There's no question about it.
I don't have the detail about that, but I think we're in a good position energy-wise to take care of our problems.
As a matter of fact, we are selling excess energy to Houston to the tune of about $16 million a year through 1985.
That helps to write off some of that initial high cost.
Water.
Our primary water source is the Colorado River, but when you get projects like Stacy Dam being approved upstream in the San Angelo area, we can see demands on the water becoming severe.
We've got about 3 trillion acre feet of water above us, so we've got plenty of water.
But there are going to be drawdowns on that upstream
There are going to be demands, continued demands downstream on that Colorado River water as far as the rice farmers and others downstream from us.
We will probably look to the Edwards Aquifer as a water resource in the future, as a secondary.
Now, you see, the Edwards Aquifer here is not the same as the one San Antonio has.
There's a tip in it from Buda on in.
Austin, it tips in our direction.
When you get north of the city, Edwards picks up and doesn't come into the Colorado, but tips toward Round Rock and Georgetown.
But Round Rock, I mean, water is something that we need to look at on down the line.
We're looking at a 2,000 population here of three-quarters of a million people in the metropolitan area.
What is it right now, Dan, to your question?
Well, the city is 350, and Travis County is four and a quarter.
So we're talking about another 300,000 people in the county by the turn of the century.
Where do you think most of those will locate?
Well, they'll locate generally north, south, northwest, and southwest.
But not much to the east.
Not much to the east.
And the problems are soils, geology, floodplains are very wide and very shallow.
We had one subdivision come in of 1,500 acres of 800 acres was in a floodplain, for example, kind of thing.
So most of it is going to be in the area that's easiest to develop, has the best access, provides the most opportunity for moderate cost housing.
It's not going to be east or west.
Water is going to be something we need to think about.
When you consider that
That increase in population moving to transportation now.
And 98% of a million person trips a day are in cars.
And consider continuing that percentage to 2 million person trips, 3 million person trips.
Yes.
In spite of the cost of gasoline.
Yes.
Individual travel by some mode is going to continue.
Let's just assume that we can change the proportion from 98.2 to 90.10
90% of two million person trips is a million eight.
We've still got 200,000 people riding in buses, but we've got a million eight riding in some kind of a vehicle.
When you consider that three-fourths of those trips are multipurpose trips and cannot be taken care of easily by a transit system, I think transportation is a very, very serious problem.
Now, how do we deal with it?
We have been encouraging employers to locate closer to subdivision areas so that people don't have to drive so far to work.
We don't insist that they locate in industrial parks.

That's the reason the planned development area site plan and industrial performance standards have been developed, so that if we get an industry to locate, that it does not negatively impact residential development around it.
We actively encourage the Chamber.
to do that.

We've actively been encouraging the Chamber to work with Chambers and other small communities within 25 miles, Georgetown, Taylor, Seguin, Round Rock, San Marcos, Bastrop, with their Chambers of Commerce, maybe to encourage some industry to locate there, to build up their economic base.
It's important that the region be a strongly
economic strength, but not so much Austin has to have all that economic strength.
We're not so sure that the CBD should be active.
We are thinking that it may not be a good idea to actively support increased development in the CBD.
Okay?
Spread it around.
What's happening to Congress Avenue?
Congress Avenue is in the hands of a task force at this moment.
to come up with some alternatives to beautification as well as handling traffic on the street.
The mandate of the council is that the street may be continued six lanes with 45-degree parking, two-way.
But in those plans, we have sidewalk extensions at all the intersections and tree planting.
and program and signage program that takes care of some of the aesthetics and pedestrian comforts as one walks the avenue.

And we're building that to see and to make sure that if the council ever wants to move to a phase two project, which may take parking to 30 degrees and reduce lanes, that we can simply expand the sidewalk out to make greater room for pedestrians.
to make sure that what we do in phase one doesn't prohibit us from moving into a second phase at some future time.
What about the creek over here?
What's its name?
Waller Creek.
Waller Creek?
Yes.
Could you describe that project?
Yes.
Waller Creek beautification is proceeding.
There is some between $1 million and $2 million of CIP money set aside for hike and bike projects.
walkways, pedestrian amenities, landscaping, bridge crossings.
That's being done by a consulting firm?
The plan was done by a consulting firm.
Which firm was it?
It was a firm out of Dallas.
Dahlberg?
Yeah.
Myron Dahlberg.
And the Parks and Recreation Department is now implementing the program.
It will include at some time a flood bypass through the center part of the city
And what will occur then along the creek is much like something like San Antonio, except not quite as significant.
There will be some structures placed in the creek to provide for ponding rather than stormwater.

And that will be from about 10th Street down to about 3rd Street, the flood bypass, so that in that business area, one can build a business and back it up to the creek and then open it up to the creek and things like that.
Very good.
But the first phase is primarily hike and bike trail from the university area, capital area, down to the lake.
And then it'll join the existing hike and bike trail.
At the lake, right.
Very good.
That's it.
All right.
Thank you very much, Dick.
You're welcome.
This is going to make a primary contribution toward the volume, I'm sure.
Well, I appreciate the opportunity that you give me to talk to you about it.
And call me, Bob, whenever, if something comes up, questions that you need answered maybe that we didn't cover or something that you want to cover that wasn't on the list.
Just give me a call.
Thank you very much.
Okay.
This is January 9, 1981.
We're at the residence of Professor Kevin Stowers of St. Edward's University.
And we're going to pick up from our conversation yesterday.
Today, it will be oriented toward the city of Austin rather than Galveston.
So Kevin, there are some questions that probably don't apply
as directly in the case of Austin and your views of it because you're not an agency director here as you were in Galveston.
But if you'd like to just go through those and comment as you feel comfortable doing so, that would be a great job.
Well, let me begin by first by saying that I would feel more comfortable in the case of Austin taking a

broader view of the overall sense of development, because I'm sure there are a lot of details and ins and outs and, in many cases, personalities that I am not as familiar with as I would be in, say, other communities where I've directly worked.
And many of these documents and dates we've already documented.
And I'm sure that you've documented many of those.
I think Austin is interesting as a community in a planning sense because
It's been at the game for a very long time for this part of the country.
I'm sure you know that the first major comprehensive plan in the community was adopted, Modern Plan, in 1928, which places it really in the forefront of modern planning efforts.
And at the same time, the city of Austin has spent, on a per capita basis, a relatively large amount of money on recreational development, planning efforts, engineering, public works, and so forth.
I think it shows in comparison to many other cities.
And the quality of what we have reflects that.
So from that reason, I'm particularly interested in what I would call kind of the transitional phase when Austin really began to grow in the 1960s and 70s.
And some of the things that I see happening in the future is the general growth in the Sun Belt has blossomed with a lot of migration into
the Sun Belt in Austin and certainly the other parts of the South.
So going that direction, although I would like to say that historically, Austin was a planned community also.
It was planned.
It was laid out on a grid system.
The capital, interestingly enough, was located precisely so that its steps were at the base of the 100-year flood plain of the Colorado River.
So this capital was not located in the center of the community, as you might traditionally expect.

But with waterborne transportation, you find that a lot of the retail and warehousing development, commercial development, occurred between the capital and the river itself, where the risk of the periodic flood was certainly
worth the technological difficulties of moving commodities and goods from the river to the warehouses to be sold to consumers.
And so you can see a historical development there that's continued through this time.
And the street system largely is dependent very much on the physiography and terrain.
It reflects how Austin related to areas outside of the region, other cities, communities, its transportation system.
And a lot of what we see happening today continues on that historical tradition that was laid down when Austin was laid out.
As I mentioned, the Capitol is located as a very valuable and central piece of property up out of the floodplain.

It was interesting that the first state prison was located right down on the river, right next to it, where if there was a good flood, it would certainly save the taxpayers a little money in the next fiscal year.
which is kind of an interesting philosophy.
But I think that you can begin to see how people in that period treated physical development and land uses.

The south side of the town, which is perhaps the one I'm most interested in because of some interns I've been working with and neighborhood associations, as well as just the fact that it seems to be where things are beginning to happen in a big way, as well as St. Edward's being located in the south side.
It was very late in developing historically.
Part of it is simply the barriers to transportation formed by the river.
And I don't know if you've had a chance to examine the 1928 plan.
Not yet.
Dick Lilly has copies of all of them in the library.
OK.
I was going to say, also, if they did not maintain copies, the Austin-Travis County collection
at the public library downtown, right next to the brand new library.
The old library maintains a complete collection of all municipal documents, memorandums, minutes of meetings.
So in the case of Austin, we have a very good historical record as opposed to Galveston and perhaps many other communities.
So that is a resource that would certainly be worth
you know, exploring and pursuing.
And there are reprints available of some of these maps and aerial views and perspectives of the city through different periods of time beginning in the 1830s moving forward to the modern period.
And I think that kind of illustration is helpful.
Very interesting to include.
And so that would certainly be one thing that I would be looking for forward to including.
Kevin, I asked Dick Lilly.
In summary, a question that I'd like to ask you.

Could you take a look at Austin as a whole and at this point in time, which seems to be somewhat critical in terms of Austin's development, enumerate maybe very few principle problems that face Austin from a planning point of view?
What opportunities do you see, perhaps, on the horizon for Austin?
Well, I guess I've been kind of optimistic, or I've just been looking at things happening, because I haven't really named problems in the way I've been looking at Austin and thinking about it.
Certainly, I think Austin, unlike a lot of communities in Texas and perhaps across the United States,

is in the position of having opportunities, and perhaps more opportunities than they have problems, which is kind of an encouraging difference from a lot of communities I've worked with and been associated with.
In fact, there seem to be so many more strengths that you're not in the situation of running around with a fire bucket trying to put out emergencies.
Now, I think if you're on city staff in a city like Austin, it seems like they're all emergencies, but in reality,
In many cases, it's opportunities.
We can talk about things that are happening in Austin that have real planning significance by the dozens.
And I would include things like rapid growth.
You certainly have a very rapid growth in population occurring in Austin.
It's moving from being one of the nice, small, medium, quite state capitals with the state university located therein
to being a major city.

If our population projections are accurate, and they've been pretty well right on up to this point, we would expect to see conceivably the city of Austin being the size of Dallas or larger by the year 2000, which is mind-boggling right now.
Indeed.
Yes.
Do you think the infrastructure could handle that?
Well, that's one of the potential problems.
I'm not so quite as concerned about the infrastructure in this case as I am about the environment.
Because if you begin looking at the physical environmental limitations of Austin, it's a remarkable site.
And that's one of the things that makes it attractive.
You're in a transition zone, really, between three major plant community ecosystem groups.
You're transitioning from the rolling hill country, basically cedar breaks, limestone hills, aquifer recharge areas down into the Texas coastal plain, heavy clay soils to the north, farm communities.
And you've got a tremendous divergency.
There's a tremendous number of creeks.
It's an extremely wet, viable, complicated area.
The terrain is hilly.
It's rolling.
It breaks sharply.
This particular house is located virtually at the edge of the Balcones Fault.
You can go less than a mile or so to the west, and suddenly you're into the hill country.
You go a couple of three miles to the east, and you're suddenly on flat, heavy clay soils.
This makes a big difference in the way things have got to happen if we're going to retain the kind of environmental character that we care for.
Now, we don't have much of an air pollution problem in Austin, and we probably won't.
Do you think the environmental character can be maintained with that many people at it?
Well, I think that's going to be very difficult to do.
I haven't sat down with a pen and pencil and done any calculations.

I think that conceivably, just looking at the map in terms of the areas that it would be possible to build in without having some sort of environmental trade-offs, that we can certainly probably double the population without increasing density.
That's just mapping the area and saying, okay, where are floodplains or recharge areas, areas which show soil limitations for construction, steep slopes, the traditional things.
So, yeah, we can grow a lot.
The only question, of course, is where, in fact, are we going to be growing?
That's one problem.
The infrastructure to support that growth gets a little bit complex because it seems like, for various reasons,
We are not growing really the directions that would be most environmentally acceptable.
And we don't seem to be really north and south, and what has been determined to be the growth corridor.
And could you stop the tape?
Excuse me.
As I was saying, which would be really north and south,
Also, the real temptation and desirable areas from those who can afford to buy houses today is to move into the hill country.
It's very attractive, beautiful views, nice area to live in.
Certainly, that's where anybody with class and taste wants to live.
And they would like to look at the unblemished hillside across from them.
But of course, people want to buy on that unblemished hillside across from them.
And then they're upset when they look out and see their neighbor's roofs and backyards and patios and so forth.
All of this compounds into tremendous erosion and runoff problems.
The cost of servicing the area is very high from a lift station standpoint, road maintenance.
The number of lots that you can get in with any degree of efficiency is very limited.
So you're talking about a lower density consuming much larger amounts of land and probably with fairly great trade-offs going
East, which is a flat area, you wind up with some...
He's a friendly cat.
I'll try to stroke you.

So anyway, you go east, you wind up with some trade-offs in terms of having a major Air Force base over there with rather loud jets flying over that just rattle your windows and drive you absolutely crazy.
You wind up with...
rather heavy clay soils, some shrink-swell problems similar to College Station and Bryan.
You wind up with limitations in terms of the structures and type of structures to build.
You're getting into prime agricultural soils.
And again, there are some trade-offs there that create problems.
What about transportation?
With a doubling or a tripling of the population, do you see anything in store for that?
Oh, I think just basically catastrophe.

I don't think that there's adequate funding available, and I don't look for it to become available any time in the near future to do the kind of massive development activities, either in terms of mass transit or highway funding that would be necessary to sustain that level of growth.
I think transportation is probably going to be one of the critical infrastructure factors that will limit
development in this and many other cities in the United States.
And the outcome, of course, is that in a city like Austin, we essentially have only one major corridor north-south.
That's IH 35, which is essentially at capacity.
It backs up in traffic jams for about an hour and a half or so during rush hour, two hours during rush hour, every day if you happen to be on it.
from 7 to 8 in the morning or from about 4 to 6 o'clock, particularly trying to get across the Colorado River.
Trying to cross the river going north to south is a very difficult proposition.
We have a fairly large number of bridges, but there's a lot of movement back and forth.
And that exceeds the capacity of those bridges during rush hour.
Now, certainly this isn't the level or magnitude of problem that parts of Dallas or Houston is facing.
But on the other hand, there aren't many places in the United States that have that level of magnitude or level of problem.
What Austin is facing is the prospect of beginning to have that level of problem.
Mopac Expressway has been built, at least in the north portion, but it doesn't really alleviate anything.
We have three major roads in the city of Austin, 183, Ben White, and IH 35, that have horrible accident rates.

The development pattern on 183 and Ben White has stripped development of the worst type with no control of access whatsoever, tremendous turning movements, U-turns, a large number of driveways per facility.
And this just compounds the problem.
And there's no acceleration or deacceleration lanes.
There's a narrow right-of-way.
The land is extremely expensive.
And any attempt to alleviate the congestion

increasing the facility or its size is going to wind up with some real difficulties real expenses that are probably beyond the ability of the highway department or the city to undertake are the city's development standards adequate it makes one me question whether they are or not if ben white for example has as many problems i would say that there's a real imbalance
between city land development standards, commercial development standards, as they apply to street capacity and street design in the city of Austin.
I'm not sure if it's a problem with the standards or some historical things that have happened or a lack of controls.
I think there are some problems there.
And I haven't looked at it well enough to know what the problem is.
But allowing a 183 and a to happen,
And having those types of land use controls that would permit that kind of traffic situation to happen indicates some real problems.
Now, I don't know if the problems in the urban city transportation department are in terms of the inability to control zoning.
Zoning is another issue that's interesting in Austin, because right now they're in the process, or they may have, they're still in the process of trying to adopt a new zoning ordinance.
I don't know if that's been mentioned to you or not.
Yes, it has.
Glover, who is actually doing the design of the ordinance now, we're in the same class at Berkeley.
Yeah, very good.
There might be hope.
Yes, he's very good, very pleasant guy.
I think that that's part of the problem, and I think the city recognizes the land use controls have got problems.
They don't like to come out and say those things too directly.
It doesn't do them much good politically or otherwise to say that they've got a real catastrophe on their hands.
But the ordinance is an old one.
It was apparently adopted many decades ago.
I think about 54.
Yeah.
I was going to say 48 or 54, somewhere in there.
And it was copied from the standard ordinances that were being written in the 30s and 40s.
Exactly.
And in the 20s.
And in the 20s, for that matter.
And it just compounded a lot of problems.
There's a lot of land that's mis-zoned for all practical purposes.
causes a lot of turmoil.
It doesn't tend to stabilize neighborhoods.
You see a lot of neighborhoods in change and fluctuation simply because the land is somewhat inappropriately zoned.
It's terribly complex when you start changing a zoning ordinance in a comprehensive way to get the thing passed because there are so many people that have so much to lose.
So I sympathize with that.
Mopac, if it is finished, and it will be,
and extended across the river.
To Ravenswood, is it?
Well, past Barton Square.
I can't remember where it ends now.
But when it's extended across the river, it's going to do some things.

And it's interesting that we're talking about this, because about three months ago, I had a student that was working for one of the neighborhood associations ask me what seemed to be the most dramatic kinds of things that affected development in South Austin.

And I pointed to what I thought were two decisions that were made really back in the early 60s, and in some cases actually going back 30 and 40 years, although certain people don't like you to know that those decisions were made 30 and 40 years ago, that tremendously impacted South Austin.
One was the cleaning up of Town Lake, changing it from a sewer to a fairly decent linear park system.
which, you know, I don't argue with, but at the same time, that changed the character and the type of investment that's going to be attracted to it.

Suddenly, instead of it being small shops and stores and neighborhood service facilities, you're beginning to look at some people that might be interested in building major hotels or convention centers.
And sure enough, that's exactly what's happening once the population mass and the activities level got to a point that suddenly people were interested in that kind of investment.
No one's mentioned this before.
Well, once it's there and the population enlarges to a certain critical point,
And you've got a beautiful park facility, a water relationship.
And it's close into downtown, into governmental centers.
And you're within, really, 10 minutes of the Capitol.
And in reality, you're not that far from the University of Texas.
Of course, that's very logical.
And you look at it, it's old, junky facilities that are run down.
And you've got, in many cases, people that acquired the land and put it together because they thought possibly something was going to happen.
And sure enough, you wind up with convention type hotels going in.
And this wipes out several blocks of relatively moderate income housing and lower scale commercial development.
This wrecks all kinds of havoc on the ensuing neighborhoods down to Ben White because it kind of has a rippling effect.
And another thing that is impacting was the decision to build Mopac as an expressway, a west loop.
The decision was first kind of pinned out by some anonymous bureaucrat in the highway department 40 years ago, if I can believe what I've been told.
He kind of looks at it and says, well, let's see what this looks like.
And of course, from an engineering standpoint, it was not an unreasonable decision.
You follow the railroad grade.
Railroad engineers weren't stupid.
They followed the easy way in and out of places.
And it kind of made some sense.
And you didn't catch anybody's house that was too important.
But unfortunately, it was close enough for Smilin, Ralph Yarborough, and a few other illustrious accolades of Texas politics to hear the noise.
And there's been no end to the complaints ever since.
And it became a political issue.
And of course, people sometimes use these things
advance their own interests, particularly if they're very powerful or influential politicians.
Interestingly enough, the sound barrier that they put up on Mopac is totally ineffective.
All it did was create a psychological feeling, a visible manifestation that the government agency was responsive and that the sound has been listened.
Actually, the sound levels, if you measure them, are well within
Normally acceptable levels, as established by the EPA, are any other group that you want to utilize.
There is no sound pollution problem on Mopac in terms of residential adjoining land uses.
However, it was a nice political issue.
It created a lot of neighborhood backlash, and there were certain outs that wished they were in politically.
